  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\delta S}{\\delta \\phi}=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Expanded Field Form.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^T_a\\nabla^{T\\,a}\\phi\n+\n\\frac{\\partial V_T}{\\partial \\phi}\n+\n\\mathcal{C}_{RT}\n+\n\\mathcal{C}_{\\tau}\n=\n0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nStarting from the action:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nS[\\phi]\n=\n\\int_M\n\\mathcal{L}_T\n\\left(\n\\phi,\\nabla^T\\phi,g\n\\right)\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^n x ,\n\\end{equation}\n\nphysical fields satisfy the stationarity condition:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\delta S}{\\delta\\phi}=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe kinetic contribution produces the Trawinistic Laplacian term:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^T_a\\nabla^{T\\,a}\\phi .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe potential contribution produces:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\partial V_T}{\\partial \\phi}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nAdditional curvature and torsion couplings are collected as:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{C}_{RT}\n+\n\\mathcal{C}_{\\tau}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nTherefore the field equation takes the form:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\nabla^T_a\\nabla^{T\\,a}\\phi\n+\n\\frac{\\partial V_T}{\\partial \\phi}\n+\n\\mathcal{C}_{RT}\n+\n\\mathcal{C}_{\\tau}\n=\n0 .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe Trawinistic field equation combines kinetic propagation, TZP potential response, curvature coupling, and torsion-localized correction.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
